column168: A chemical odor was reported to be coming from GATX 66427. Upon inspection it was determined that  both the vacuum relief valve and the manway had vapor releases. The vacuum relief valve was removed and a plug was put in its place. The manway had 5 out of 6 manway hinged swing bolts less then tool  tight and had both a nozzle gasket and a lid gasket installed. The lid gasket was removed and the  manway was then secured. These actions stopped the vapor release.

At approximately 12 noon, material handler was loading bleach into the MiniBulk tanker.  The operator, while monitoring the loading operations, stopped the load out when he observed bleach coming out of the dome.  Subsequent investigation determined that 52 gallons of bleach was spilled into containment.  All material was recovered and no injuries or exposures occurred.  It was discovered that the trailer was not weighed in at the end of the previous day and material handler visually observed the heel inside the tanker from the prior day.  He thought he had sufficient ullage to complete the intended loading of the trailer but miss gauged the heel amount.  Thus the tanker overfilled into containment.
column169: A bulk loading checklist / form has been implemented for all bulk loading or unloaded at this facility.  A part of the checklist requires operator to verify sufficient space/ullage prior to moving forward with the bulk transfer.

column168: On April 9, 2019 at 1420 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics terminal XRQ regarding a release that occurred the previous day at an unknown time on April 8, 2019. The caller was very unsure of a lot. She estimated that approximately 1 quart of UN1263, Paint (flammable), 3, PGII "Zinsser BIN Primer" had released from at least 1 (1) quart metal pail inside of a box with 6 quarts total. She wasn't sure exactly what product this was on the BOL sent over which had a list with many products on it. None of the products had a UN number on it but when locating the SDS for the trade name of the picture sent over, it was declared hazardous. She said that a box containing (2) 1-gallon metal cans of a non regulated primer were also at the very least impacted and maybe damaged. She stated that the UN1263 paint had released to the trailer floor of trailer 3175454, but the trailer was never cleaned up and had already left the terminal. She stated the damaged and impacted cans were placed on a pallet on the dock. After reviewing the SDS with the caller, she stated that the terminal could place these 6 (1) quart damaged pails inside of (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The other (2) 1-gallon pails were placed inside a separate 55-gallon metal drum. All waste was staged on site for the terminal to manage.

column168: The box was properly marked and labeled, however the DOT-31FP was marked on the brown fiberboard box in a black magic marker. Based on my 32 years of DG experience as an inspector, auditor and instructor, the fact there are no closure instructions for Packing Instruction 200 for UN 1072 and the package looked like it had been reused more than once and the hand marking of DOT-31FP.while allowable did not have any feel for authenticity, I chose to open the box. I wanted to verify if the package contained any measures that would preclude flame penetration or provide thermal resistance. Upon opening the box I found a plain brown fiberboard sleeve surrounding the green metal-cylinder, some bubble wrap yet none of the components that make a DOT-31FP, a DOT-31FP. I took some preliminary pictures and forwarded them to FAA Hazmat Manager Stan Satchell and FAA FedEx PHIs Ryan Pohlke& Steven Redeker. The package is on hold pending an FAA inspection. The FAA was notified electronically.

column168: At 1110 ET, ETRS was notified by Earl Coggins with Landstar regarding a cargo release.  According to the caller, a 2,370 pound tote and a 474 pound 55-gallon drum of UN 2924, Flammable Liquid, Corrosive, N.O.S. "Water Clarifier 'RBW 85178'" released to the top of the containers due to possibly loose caps.  There was no impact to any drains, soils, or waterways.  Due to the size of the containers a DOT report was required.  ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental for the clean up response. Contractor arrived at 1225 ET and confirmed the product in the 55 gallon drum was leaking from the cap. Contractor over packed the drum to send onto the consignee in place of breaking the seal and contaminating the product. At 1246 the contractor located the tote and confirmed it was leaking from the valve and would need a transfer into a new tote. At 1257 the tote transfer began. The new tote of product was shipped with the over packed drum to the consignee. At 1319 the transfer was completed and the contractor removed the empty tote for disposal.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON THE FLOOR OF A TUCK IN DOOR 4. I SAW A YELLOW LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BOX. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS ON THE BOX. I PUT ON MY PPE AND MOVED THE BOX TO THE DMP AREA. IT WAS AFTER THE PRELOAD THAT I OPENED THE BOX TO DISCOVER A 5 GALLON BUCKET MARKED WITH A "FLAMMABLE LIQUID 3" HAZMAT STICKER AND "UN1263". THE BOX WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED WITH ANY TYPE OF HAZMAT STICKERS AND THEREFORE COULD'VE RESULTED IN INJURY IF TOUCHED. SOMEONE DID NOT DO THEIR JOB PROPERLY OF MAKING SUR THE BOX WAS LABELED WITH HAZMAT STICKERS AND PAPERS. TO ME, IT LOOKED LIKE A REGULAR BOX LEAKING A YELLOW LIQUID, I INITIALLY THOUGHT IT WAS MUSTARD.
column169: PROPERLY LABEL HAZMATS WITH APPROPRIATE STICKERS AND PAPERS BEFORE SHIPPING. I AM GUESSING THE SHIPPER WANTED TO CUT CORNERS AND COSTS BY NOT LABELING IT AS A HAZMAT BEFORE SHIPPING WITH THE UPS SYSTEM. IT WAS SENT AS A REGULAR BOX WHEN IT SHOULD'VE BEEN SENT AND LABELED AS A HAZMAT.

column168: On April 17, 2019 at 0815 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics temrinal UDV regarding a hazardous cargo release. column168: On April 19, 2019 at 0209 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal UKC regarding a hazardous cargo release that occurred on April 18, 2019 at 2240 EST. The terminal confirmed that approximately 0.5 ounce of UN1170, Ethanol, solution, 3, PGIII released near the cap of the drum while in transit presumably due to shaking while in transit and the cap not being completely secured. The terminal confirmed that there was no damaged to the drum and no product was leaking after the cap was tightened. After reviewing the SDS with the caller, he stated that the terminal felt comfortable cleaning the released product with the appropriate PPE. The terminal shipped the drum onto the consignee because it was not damaged. The waste generated was put inside (1) 5-gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D for the terminal.

column168: On April 19, 2019 at 11:45 EST, XPO Logistics- NNA experienced an approximate 2-ounces of UN3266, corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s., 8, PGII " Cor Clene 326K" release from one (1) 1,200-gallon poly tote. Released material impacted dock floor, no drains, soil or waterways were impacted by the release. The incident is a result of punctured container due to forklift incident. After reviewing the SDS with XPO-personnel it was determined due to the nature of the material a contractor should be dispatched for cleanup. ERTS dispatched Hepaco from Nashville, TN. Hepaco personnel arrived onsite at 0615 EST and assessed release. It was confirmed the release of 2-ounces due to puncture at the top of tote impacting the outside of the container. Contractor transferred recovered material into new container utilizing diaphragm pump and hoses, tote will continue with shipment. The damaged tote was cut up and placed into (1) 55-gallon metal drum and rinse water from pump decon was placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged in OS&D for terminal to manage proper disposal.
This shipment consisted of 24 pails and 24 drums of UN3265. One of the drums had a loose bung which caused some product to leak out.

column168: On April 23, 2019 at 0845 EST, XPO Logistics LDA terminal experienced a 55-gallon UN1760, Corrosive Liquid, n.o.s., 8, PGIII from (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The release impacted trailer 3132880 floor and asphalt area below. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. Release was a result of punctured drum due to forklift incident. After reviewing SDS it was determined that a contractor should be dispatch for clean up. Lone Star Hazmat from Dallas, TX was dispatched. Contractor personnel arrived onsite and confirmed one (1) 55-gallon drum had been punctured and released all contents impacting a 8' x 20' area of the trailer floor and a 8' x 40' area of asphalt. Soda ash was utilized to neutralize material and placed absorbent material to capture material. The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 85 poly open-top drum and the neutralized and impacted absorbents and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly open-top drums. All waste was staged in OS&D for terminal to manage proper disposal.

On April 23, 2019 at 2350 EST, XPO Logistics XCN terminal experienced an approximate 5-gallon UN3352, Pyrethroid Pesticide, Liquid, Toxic, 6.1 PGIII "Capture LFR Insecticide" release from one (1) box containing two (2) 2.5-gallon plastic jugs. Release impacted trailer 3175386 and dock floors. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was a result of a puncture to containers due to forklift incident. After reviewing SDS it was determined that a contractor would need to be dispatched to handle clean up. Environmental Management Specialists of Cincinnati, OH was dispatched to terminal. Contractor personnel arrived onsite and confirmed one (1) box containing two (2) 2.5-gallon containers was punctured and has released approximately 5-gallons to trailer and dock floors impacting a 5' x 8' area. Absorbent material was utilized to absorb released material and collected. The damaged container and box were containerized into one (1) 10-gallon metal drum and the impacted absorbents and debris were containerized into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. All waste was staged in OS&D for terminal to manage proper disposal.

column168: The driver of the vehicle stopped at a truck stop for a break. Upon returning to the vehicle he discovered a puddle by rear cargo doors and he contacted FedEx Custom Critical (FCC). I requested that he check with the truck stop staff to see if they had a barrier they could put around the vehicle to contain the leak to the immediate area while I worked on getting a hazmat response agency on-site. The truck stop did not have a barrier so they contacted the Greenup Fire department that arrived with a barrier and they waited in the area until the hazmat response team arrived.  The hazmat agency immediately discovered one leaking drum that had a structural failure near the base. They cleaned the interior of the truck as best they could on-site as well as the involved pavement area in the truck stop parking lot. The agency requested that the driver return to their shop for additional cleaning so they could remove all the freight since the failed drum was located in the nose of the box. The hazmat agency was on-site at the truck stop for approximately 2 hours.  After arriving at their site and moving the freight they discovered a second leaking drum caused by a nail protruding up from the skid into the bottom of the barrel. All freight was removed from the vehicle, it was cleaned, the partially filled drum was placed in an overpack for disposal, and all waste held for disposal by our hazmat agent.
column169: When the parent company of the consignee, Chemours, was notified of the leak they indicated that the freight was likely to be leaking and that the shipment had been set up to return the freight. I think better training should be in place because if the drums were suspected of failure or had already failed, they should have been repackaged prior to additional transportation.

The car was isolated and the shipper Citgo Petroleum Corp, was notified. Hazmat Manager Rob James found product had leaked around the bottom outlet valve, the valve had product on all sides of the bottom outlet valve. Hazmat Manager James attempted to tighten the secondary closure valve but was unable to.  The issue was identified and all actions were communicated to the shipper, Citgo Petroleum (Jeff 518-392-5370). Hazmat Manager James worked with local CSX Transportation and International Paper (JM King 843-833-9293) to get the tank car spotted in International Paper and immediately get it off loaded. This did require a special move.

column168: On April 17, 2019 at 1522 EST, XPO Logistics terminal USA experienced an approximate 1-pint UN1090, Acetone, 3, PGII release. All material released was contained to trailer 3112439 floor. The release was a result of forklift puncture. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release. After reviewing SDS it was determined XPO personnel had proper PPE and material to clean release safely. The impacted containers and damaged container were placed into one (1) 25-gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D for terminal to manager proper disposal.

column168: On April 17, 2019 at 0321 EST, XPO Logistics terminal XSW experienced a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading approximately 4 ounces of haz UN1133 Rema Bond SC4000 released from a 55 gallon metal drum. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the dock floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and they felt comfortable cleaning the release with granular absorbents and the proper PPE. The released product and damaged 55 gallon metal drum will be placed in an 85 gallon metal drum and be staged in the wste area for terminal to manager proper disposal.

column168: DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED ON A SPLIT LOAD FOR 2 LEASES THAT ARE ON THE SAME LEASE PAD. PUMPER REQUESTED THAT THE DRIVER UNLOAD THE 1ST LEASE AND EMPTY THE TANK SO THAT THE PUMPER COULD REPLACE A BAD VALVE. DRIVER SAID THE TANK WAS TAKING A LONG TIME TO LOAD AND HE SUSPECTED RUST WAS LODGED IN THE HEADER VALVE. DRIVER FINISHED THE FIRST LOAD AND PULLED UP TO LOAD THE 2ND TANK. DRIVER STARTED LOADING AND BROKE POLICY BY LEAVING THE PUMP ENGAGED AND WENT TO CLOSE THE VALVE ON THE 1ST TANK. HE WAS HAVING TROUBLE WITH THE VALVE. HE ALSO SAID HE BACK GAUGED THE 1ST TANK AND WHEN HE LOOKED OVER OIL WAS RUNNING OUT OF HIS VENT LINE ONTO THE GROUND. DRIVER RAN OVER TO MITIGATE THE INCIDENT. IN A PANIC, THE DRIVER STATED HE DISENGAGED THE PUMP AND GRABBED HIS SHOVEL TO MAKE A DAM. OIL KEPT COMING OUT AND HE RAN BACK OVER AND REALIZED HIS PUMP WAS STILL IN THE LOAD POSITION. HE CLOSED THE BELLY VALVE AND WENT BACK OVER TO FINISH THE DAM. WE HE WENT BACK TO REVERSE THE PUMP, THE BELLY VALVE BEING CLOSED CAUSED A VACUUM ON THE TANKER, HE HAD TO OPEN THE BELLY VALVE WHICH CAUSED MORE OIL TO BURP OUT ONTO THE GROUND. HE WAS FINALLY ABLE TO PUMP BACK INTO THE TANK.
column169: DURING THE INVESTIGATION, THE DRIVER HAD TO SWITCH TRAILERS NUMEROUS TIMES AND THE INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT THE OVERFILL PROTECTION WAS NOT PLUGGED IN. WE ARE WORKING ON REWIRING OUR FLEET TO ELIMINATE THIS ISSUE AND WE HAVE ALREADY IMPLEMENTED A LEARNING FROM INCIDENT WERE WAS WE ARE RE-TRAINING ALL OF OUR CURRENT DRIVERS AND OUR NEW HIRES IN ORIENTATION ON HOW TO IDENTIFY AN UNPLUGGED OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE DURING A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION.

column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: DRIVER, BRIAN HALL WAS TRAVELING ON STATE HIGHWAY 35 APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION OF FM 1468 IN HEAVY RAIN. AS MR. HALL APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION, HE NOTICED A VEHICLE A VEHICLE APPROACHING A SET BACK STOP SIGN. THAT VEHICLES DRIVER APPEARED TO BE UNPREPARED TO STOP. MR. HALL TOOK EVASIVE ACTION RESULTING IN THE SHIFT OF CARGO (SULFURIC ACID TOTES). AS A RESULT, SEVEN (7) TOTES WERE THROWN FROM THE TRAILER RESULTING IN A SULFURIC ACID RELEASE ONTO THE ROADWAY AND SHOULDER SOIL. THE RELEASE WAS SUDDEN AND ACCIDENTAL. OIL MOP, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROVIDER, WAS CONTACTED TO CONDUCT EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND CONTAINMENT MEASURES. A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 17,000 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID AND RAIN WATER WAS COLLECTED FOR NEUTRALIZATION AND DISPOSAL. IMPACTED SOIL EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED FOR DISPOSAL. PH SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED FOR VERIFICATION AND CONFIRMATION OF REMEDIAL EFFORTS.
column169: RECOMMENDATION:  #1. CORRECT THE STOP SIGN LOCATION! AFTER DISCUSSIONS WITH LOCAL POLICE/FIREFIGHTERS/STATE POLICE - THE INTERSECTION LOCATION IF THE ACCIDENT IS THE MOST FAULTED (ACCIDENTS) LOCATION WITHIN THE COUNTY. THE STOP SIGN IS 30'S BEHIND THE LINE OF STOP. THIS GIVES THE APPEARANCE THAT A VEHICLE IS NOT STOPPING AT THE SIGN AND IS CONTINUING INTO THE INTERSECTION. THIS PARTICULAR ACCIDENT WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED IF THE STOP SIGN WAS IN A PROPER LOCATION. THE DRIVER WOULD NOT HAVE HAD TO USE EVASIVE MEASURES AND HARD STOPPING HAD THE STOP SIGN BEEN AT A PROPER LOCATION.  #2. LOADING AND SECUREMENT PROCEDURES: TRANSPORTATION COMPANY IS IN THE PROCESS IF A COMPREHENSIVE REVIEW OF DIFFERENT LOADING AND SECUREMENT PROCEDURES TO MIGRATE FUTURE SHIFTING OF LOADS DUE TO EVASIVE DRIVING AND HARD BRAKING.  #3. EQUIPMENT REVIEW: ANOTHER AREA OF REVIEW IS THE DIFFERENT TYPES OF SECUREMENT EQUIPMENT. STRAPS, CHAINS AND PALLETS - USE IN COMBINATION WITH EACH TO MAKE A MORE SECURED LOAD. CANNONBALL TRUCKING IS ALWAYS LOOKING FOR THE SAFEST PROCEDURE AND EQUIPMENT TO TRANSPORT ALL TYPES COMMODITIES.

column168: WHILE LOADING A TRAILER AT THE DOCK, IT WAS NOTED THAT A DRUM LEAK HAD OCCURRED IN THE TRAILER AND RESULTED IN 200 ML OF WASTE BEING RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT COVERED TRANSFER AREA IN THE YARD. TWO PINHOLES WERE DISCOVERED IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM ALONG WITH SCRAPE MARKS. THE SCRAPE MARKS APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BY THE DRUM GRABBER. PRELIMINARY INFORMATION PROVIDED WAS THAT THE DRUM MET THE ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO SIGN OF LEAKING AT THE TIME OF PICKUP OR TRANSPORTATION. EVIDENCE SUGGEST THAT THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED WHILE TRANSFERRING THE DRUM TO THE TRAILER USING THE DRUM GRABBER. THE DRUM WAS SUBSEQUENTLY PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM (OVERPACKED) AND THE SPILL CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT. THE DRUM GRABBER HAS BEEN PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND A REPLACEMENT DRUM GRABBER HAS BEEN ORDERED.  NOTE THE EPA HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST NUMBER: 000238821 DAT
column169: REMOVAL OF THE DRUM GRABBER FROM SERVICE. REPLACEMENT WAS ORDERED.

column168: ON APRIL 2, 2019 AT 11:43 AM, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED VIA EMAIL BY MS DOT INSPECTOR TOMMY THOMAS THAT HE "INSPECTED CAR TFOX 9323 IN HIGH OAK YARD THIS MORNING AND FOUND THE LOADED CAR LEAKING PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT IS COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER, 8 OF 8 MANWAY BOLTS UNSECURED."  KCS MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR MOUNTED TFOX 9329 AND FOUND FOUR MANWAY SWING BOLTS IN THE DOWN POSITION, AND THE OTHER FOUR SWING BOLTS INT HE UP POSITION BUT LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. LADING OUTRAGE AND MANWAY SWING BOLTS IN THE DOWN POSITION, AND THE OTHER FOUR SWING BOLTS IN THE UP POSITION BUT LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. LADING OUTRAGE AND MANWAY GASKET WERE CHECKED AND APPEARED ACCEPTABLE. THE MANWAY WAS CLOSED TOOL TIGHT, USING EVEN STAR PATTERN WITH THREE PASSES. ALL OTHER CLOSURES WERE VERIFIED TO BE TOOL TIGHT. TFOX 9329 WAS DECONTAMINATED, AND SUBSEQUENTLY RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTITY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTION. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE TO CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

AT THAT MOMENT I NOTIFIED MY RMP FOR FOLLOW-UP WITH SAID EMPLOYEE.

Original comments:  Package handler and ops manager found a hazmat in our NC trailer. The package handler noticed the package looked wet. Informed the Ops manager of the damaged hazmat. Ops manager informed Sort manager. Sort Manager pulled the SDS. Both the ops manager and package handler did not touch the wet package. However the sort manager requested they immediately rinse their hands with water as a precaution (according to the instructions on the SDS). Sort manager grabbed a hazmat tote and wore PPE gloves. Sort manager did not find any liquid in trailer. No other packages seemed to be affected. Removed damaged hazmat from the unload. There was no cleanup required. Upon inspection of hazmat, there was no liquid present other than the small wet spots/stains on package. The internal packaging was inadequate not enough filler or protection to prevent glass from breaking.  New Comments:

column168: Driver arrived at the address printed on the bills of lading.  This being his first time delivering to this site, he seek and followed the instructions of site personnel beginning with scaling in and following site instructions to check in.  After checking in/weighing pulled off scales waiting for further instructions later being told to report to the control room (in his sight from where parked).  Driver with paperwork in hand, introduce himself and stated he was to deliver a shipment of 98% acid to P&G (also at same address).  The personnel in control room reviewed the paperwork and directed driver to the unloading site.    The operator at unload site arrived was handed the shipments’ paperwork and driver begin his procedures to unload.  Once prepared to start transfer, driver questioned the storage tank capacity due to the site glass readings.  Operator confirmed there was capacity to receive the product, completed a check list and completing/signing carrier’s approval for unloading.  The driver started the transfer.  After an estimated 40 minutes of transferring, it was discovered the storage tank was overflowing and the driver engaged the emergency shutoff to cease the transfer of product.  The spilled product was contained and cleanup handled on-site by site personnel.       The spilled amount entered as 1 gallon pending confirmation of actual gallons from the consignee.

column168: At approximately 1200 hours Central Standard Time, a Safety Kleen Systems, Inc driver arrived at the customer’s location and was attempting to place a drum in an over pack and spilled approx. 20 gallons of spent Paint Thinner. Absorbent material was immediately put down the spent product was contained. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriated PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal. A report was made to Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality with the incident number 19-01617.
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the Safety Kleen Systems, Inc. driver failed to follow proper overpacking procedures which resulted in the spill. The driver was subsequently placed out of service and retrained on proper overpacking procedures per company policy.

column168: April 18, 2019 at 0916 ET, Jean Hutchins discovered a release of UN2030 "Hydrazine hydrate" 6.1, II from (3) 275 gallon metal totes due to a manufacturer defect (damaged valves). At the time of the initial discovery Jean did not know the cause of the release. An Environmental team was called to assess the area. They arrived to discover the release was cause due to (2) of the (3) leaking totes, required the atmospheric valve to be re-positioned. Then the final totes needed the top lid removed from the clamp and re-secured. Completing these tasks stopped the release of material to the trailer floor.

on April 22, 2019 at 18:20 EST, XPO Logistics terminal LDA experienced an approximate 8-gallon UN3264, Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic, n.o.s., 8, PGIII release to trailer 3111983 floor. No drains, soils or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. Due to the nature of the spill a contractor was dispatched to site. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed due to improper loading, no blocking or bracing a  pallet with a motor bolted to it fell over and gouged container and released oil into the tote contaminating the contents of the tote. It was discovered that the material has impacted the asphalt below the trailer, contractor performed pH testing on material and yielded a 4. It was determined that the release was a mixture of the oil from the motor and the UN3264 material from tote. Soda ash was applied to neutralize impacted areas. The contaminated material from the tote was transferred into five (5) 55-gallon poly drums. Contractor recovered the spent neutralizer and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged in OS&D for terminal to manage proper disposal.

At 0914 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO (NRO) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately  6 teaspoons of regulated "Alkyl Amines" UN1760 released from the cap due to not being secured tightly from (1) 2,256 pound plastic tote. The caller indicated the release was contained to the top of the tote. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined terminal personnel are capable of cleaning the release with the use of appropriate PPE, and containerized into a (1) 5-gallon DM w/double liner to be staged in OS&D for terminal to manage proper disposal. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

April 19, 2019 at 1655 ET it was discovered that a 1000 lb super sack of Antimony Trioxide had a release of 30 lbs of material to the trailer floor due to a hard and sudden load shift during transit. This released 30 lbs of material from the super sack onto the trailer floor due to a tear in the body. An environmental team was called to assist in the transfer and clean up of the spilled material.

At 2150 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics UBF regarding a hazardous cargo release.  It was reported that due to a manufacturer's defect, (1) 3-gallon poly jug containing UN325, 8, PG II, Spectrus NX1100 spilled an approximate 1-gallon to the tail of the trailer and apron.  ERTS reviewed the SDS with caller, verified that the terminal has neutralizer, PPE, and the proper waste container to complete the cleanup for this incident. The impacted absorbents, spent neutralizer and damaged container were placed into one (1) 30-gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D for terminal to manage proper disposal. No drains, soil or waterways were impacted by the release.

tank car was stationary in the yard.  Investigation revealed that juvenile trespassers, manipulated the angle cock and cut lever.  This resulted in the cars rolling on the track.  The cars rolled over a de-rail device which prevented them from entering the mainline track.  The cars rolled over onto their side.  PROX40450 leaked product from the manway lid of the car. Absorbent pads/boom and containment was placed around the manway and on the ground underneath the car. A vacuum truck was utilized to suck the product up that was captured in containment.  When the car was placed back on the track, the manway was opened and a defective manway nozzle gasket was observed.  Once the car was righted, the leak stopped.

column168: On 04/30/2019, at 0934 hours, personnel in the CSXT South Charleston, WV Yard discovered NATX 50416, a residue tank car of Potassium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the National Response Center and West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  The shipper was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2019-0430-00110). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a slow product release from the bottom outlet valve and secondary closure. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Chad Blake of Covestro, phone 304-281-4864. Contractor personnel tightened the bottom outlet valve secondary closure cap and removed all spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 149 NARRI: 90

column168: On 4/23/2019 at approximately 07:00 MST, the SOTX 1872 was observed by yard personnel to have fresh staining on the top and sides of the car.  The car was isolated and inspected by BNSF Hazmat trained personnel.  Upon inspection, one manway swingbolt was found to be less than hand tight resulting in a release from the manway seal. column169: Shipper has been notified of the NAR.  Proper post loading/pre-trip inspection practices should be reinforced with loading personnel to ensure that all fittings/closures are in place and properly tightened prior to releasing the car into transportation.(NAR:200)

column168: On April 29, 2019, at 1915 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics UTA about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading, approximately 10 pounds of DuBois Chemical HA Powder (Corrosive solid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s., UN 3262) was released from a 48-pound cardboard box. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer and dock floor. Terminal personnel cleaned up the release with the appropriate PPE. The released product, damaged cardboard box and debris was placed in a 10-gallon poly drum and staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On April 30, 2019, at 0300, ERTS was contacted by XPO logistics XQC  about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading approximately 8 ounces of Sygenta Force 6.5 G  (Pyrethroid pesticide, solid, poisonous, UN3349) released from (1) 40-pound plastic bag. The released product was contained to the dock floor. The release was cleaned up with granular absorbents and the appropriate PPE. The released product, damaged plastic bag and other debris was placed into (1) 40-gallon metal drum and staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: This was a drum staged on a pallet and strapped to the wall of a trailer. During transit two boards on the pallet that the drum was staged on broke causing the drum to shift and the strap that was securing it to fail. As a result the drum fell over and struck the pallet it was staged on which slightly punctured the drum and contributed to the unintentional release. The spilled product was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container. The punctured drum was laid on its side, secured, and repair with drum putty and successful returned to terminal where it was placed into a recovery container and eventually delivered to ultimate consignee without further incident.
column169: The only suggestion I can come up with regarding this event is to make sure the pallets chosen and used to staged drums on can support the weight of the drum and will not crack and collapse like it did in this event. In the event the pallet cannot support the load I would recommend to either repalletize or place the shipment on the floor of the trailer.

column168: TANK CAR CMRX 24985 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE B END LIQUID VALVE. THE PRODUCT WAS AUTO REFRIGERATING AND COVERING THE VALVE ASSEMBLY WITH FROST. THE LIQUID VALVE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE PARTIALLY OPEN, LEAKING AND THE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE LEAKING STOPPED. THE LOOSE PLUG WAS REMOVED, INSPECTED, HAD TEFLON TAPE APPLIED, AND THEN WAS SECURED. THE CAR WAS CHECKED AGAIN AND VERIFIED THE LEAKING STOPPED. THE VAPOR PLUG WAS NOT LEAKING BUT WAS DISCOVERED TO ALSO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  IT IS DIFFICULT TO DETERMINE THE QUANTITY RELEASED BECAUSE 1) SHIPPER WAYBILL IS AN ESTIMATED QUANTITY (157,989 LBS), 2) CAR WAS SCALED WITH A SCALE WEIGHT OF 170,700 LBS, 3) CONSIGNEE HAS NOT OFFLOADED RAILCAR.
column169: SHIPPER NEEDS TO CHECK PROCEDURES FOR VERIFYING RAILCARS ARE PROPERLY SECURED LEAVING SHIPPING FACILITY.

column168: Our truck driver stopped at the Petro Truck stop in Atlanta, GA. During his stopped he observed fumes coming from the top of the cargo tank trailer. It was raining at this time. He reported the situation to his terminal manager. Shortly after contacting his manager someone at the truck stop contacted Atlanta Fire department. On arrival they examined the trailer and reported acid was leaking around the dome area. An emergency response contractor was brought in to collect and clean the leaking material. No lined cargo tank trailer was available to transfer the acid into so the contractor transferred the acid into intermediate bulk containers. The trailer continued to leak while this process was conducted. After completing the material transfer the contractor cleaned the area. The acid in the ibc's continued to it's original destination.  It appears there was a failure of the cargo tank lining which allowed hydrocloric acid to contact the stainless steel tank shell resulting in hole in the cargo tank shell.
column169: Provide additional training to material handlers to ensure that they are implementing proper freight handling techniques and are able to recognize and prevent potential future incidents.

column168: While in route to the destination facility, driver moved from right lane to allow on coming traffic to  merge onto highway from the off ramp.  The lane to the left was clear.  As the driver moved into lane,  the passenger vehicle in front of him slammed on their brakes forcing the driver to hit his brakes   causing the trailer to swerve.  Driver pulled over immediately to check his load and found a pallet of  drums had shifted resulting in a puncture of one drum approximately 1/4 of the way down from the  top of the drum.  The driver called our internal emergency response hotline, the Elko Fire Department, and Nevada  Highway Patrol.  Due to the drum contents, flammable material, the Elko Fire Department  evacuated 2 small business nearby.  The Fire Department HazMat team used an air monitoring  device and determined there was no danger.  Evacuation was cancelled.  The drum was overpacked,  area remediated and clean-up was completed by 1900.
column169: Investigation of this incident confirmed the driver did not properly secure the pallet of drums.  Driver  has received disciplinary action, and retrained on load securement; to include but not limited to  configuration of straps.

column168: While en route to customer locations, the driver of an RSI methanol tanker fell asleep at the wheel, causing the truck to leave the left side of the road. As the driver attempted to bring the truck back onto the road, it crossed the road again, this time to the right side, where the driver over-corrected to the left, causing the truck to turn over on its right side. Approximately 2400 gallons of methanol was released into a swale adjacent to roadway, due to the abrasion and rupture of several tank compartments, as well as failure/leaking of product from top hatches. Initial estimates were a release rate of 10 gpm or so; however, this slowed considerably as liquid levels fell below top hatches. Cuero VFD and state troopers closed FM 766 as a precaution and attempted to place booms to slow advance of methanol but tall grass prevented effective response. Victoria FD Regional Hazmat and CG Environmental (private spill response contractor) were dispatched to scene and arrived by 14:00, at which point tanker no longer leaking, and liquid level below hatches. RSI personnel from Cuero Yard were dispatched to scene with a flatbed, empty IBC's (totes), and a pump and remaining product (approximately 525 gallons) off-loaded into totes and truck righted by 19:00. A Texas Commission of Environmental Quality (TCEQ) Region 14 (Corpus Christi) investigator supervised response actions and follow-up sampling of soils in vicinity of spill; results were indicative of no impact. It is speculated that due to prevailing wind and weather conditions during the incident, the vast majority of released product volatilized into the atmosphere. Some distressed vegetation was observed in the vicinity of the rollover in the days following the incident. No water bodies (e.g. Guadalupe River) were impacted as a result of the incident.
column169: RSI has communicated the details of this incident company-wide and reviewed its operating policies and procedures with drivers; specifically, the need to be abreast of changes in medical status and medicine dosages.  In this case, the driver was impaired due to taking a higher than recommended dose of a required medication - the dose had changed but the driver had forgotten and inadvertently took twice the recommended dose. In addition, the driver complained of fatigue and had been evaluated for a sleep disorder.  This information fell outside the scope of the normal DOT physical and so was not disclosed to RSI, according to the post-incident investigation.  RSI is working to reinforce its "Stop Work Authority" policy and exploring ways employees can communicate any physical, medical or other limitations in their ability to perform their job duties so the appropriate steps can be taken to provide rest, alternate (lower risk) work tasks, or other accommodation to prevent the recurrence of an incident like this. All of these steps are worth taking by all companies involved in hazardous materials transportation.

column168: 1 Driver #395802 ‘Max Meier’ arrived at the consignee ‘Energy Transfer Partners’ in Aston, PA to offload product: Keropur AP 205 20M at 1300 on 4/18/19   2 Driver set up unload, opening dome to vent trailer in preparation of pump unload    3 During offload process, product began to leak from the packing nut on the external valve assembly, into driver’s catch bucket   4 The consignee and driver attempted to fix the leak by tightening the nut over the assembly.  Driver did not have extra packing material which fixes most common issues with this part of the valve.   5 Knowing the leak was secure for transport (just not for offloading) the driver left the consignee to go and get the problem fixed    6 Driver claims he completed a pre-trip to include a dome lid check to ensure it was secure    7 As driver exited the plant on to Market street, the product began to spill, impacting approximately 500 feet of roadway.    8 Driver noted he heard a rushing sound, and something didn’t sound right and then noticed product coming from the trailer in his mirrors.     9 Driver stopped, got out, realized product was coming down the rainwater drain tubes from the crash box and had spilled on to the roadway.   10  In his hurry to secure the spill, he attempted to plug the drain tubes to contain it, and did not Don his required PPE.    11 Despite successfully plugging the drain tubes, product got on driver’s arms and legs   12 Driver checked the top of trailer, claims everything was secure and has no idea how the product released    13 As verified by spill response company, 75 gallons spilled in total from within the plant to the roadway where driver stopped   14 Spill response company verified all up top was secure when they got to the scene    15 A fire department chief witnessed the driver pull over and pulled behind him to assist. Driver stated his legs and arms had a burning sensation    16 Fire Department Chief called an ambulance who set up a portable decontamination station and rinsed driver with water. Transported him to the hosptial for evaluation. Driver was given hydrocortisone/aquaphorine as treatment and released   17 The tractor/trailer were staged at the consignee lot, as it was in close proximity. A Schneider Safety Team associate went to the consignee location and identified the source of the initial unload problem. During the last clean out, the tankwash disassembled the QRB, cleaned it and reassembled, but the crunch ring used to apply pressure on the Teflon packing material was put on backwards in error by the Tankwash facility.    18 The safety team corrected the issue on site, and the load was safely unloaded without further incident

column168: On 4/15/2019 at 9:30AM a PVS Distribution driver noticed liquid on the floor of his trailer. Upon further inspection, the driver found that a tote of Cleaner#2A was leaking. The tote was removed from the trailer and placed in a safe area where the product could be properly contained. The operations supervisor and another employee suited up in the appropriate PPE and used Soda Ash to absorb the product that was on the floor of the trailer. They also created a c like around the tote using Soda Ash. While the leaking tote was being dealt with, a second PVS Distribution driver went to a customers site and retrieved an empty tote of Cleaner #2A. Once the empty tote arrived, product in the damaged tote was transferred into the empty tote. The final cleanup was completed and all contaminated materials were placed into an appropriate recovery waste drum.
column169: The damaged tote was transferred to another PVS Distribution site where it was thoroughly inspected . A 4" crack was found about 1/3 of the way up from the bottom of the tote. The crack was along a mold seam of the tote. The tote was last inspected and certified in September of 2017. The PVS Distribution Painesville Leadership team met with all of their Material Handlers and Drivers to discuss the incident and reinforce proper tote handling procedures. At this time, the root cause investigation has concluded that all applicable procedures, processes and policies were followed.

column168: While filling the stationary tank(from the tanker truck), the level gauge on the tank stopped working, giving a false reading. The product flowed out of the tank overflow and was released into the secondary containment berm for the tank. Upon investigation, we believe that the gauge may have become air-locked during the unloading operation. It is now functioning properly. The product was recovered from the concrete secondary containment berm and will be neutralized prior to disposal at a permitted solid waste landfill.
column169: Unloading procedures have been reviewed and future unloading will be closely monitored at a slower pace to preventing air-locking of the gauge.

column168: Driver failed to check if the bleeder valve in the pod was closed before beginning to offload and failed to maintain being in attendance resulting in the pod overflowing and spilling onto the ground.
column169: All drivers in the company were retrained in the importance of remaining in attendance and checking all valves before beginning loading or unloading. Training specific to bleeder valves was also implemented to prevent occurrence.

column168: On April 26, 2019 at approximately 1500 ET, a Page Trucking tractor-trailer truck, transporting 22,526 kilograms (kg) or 49,661 pounds of aluminum-polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) hazardous waste (UN3432), was involved in a single-vehicle accident that resulted in the truck rolling-over on its side causing a release of the hazardous waste to the roadside median soils and ditch-swale within the median. No storm drains or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. There were no fires, threats of fires, evacuations or threats of evacuations. On April 26, 2019 at approximately 1700 ET, Ace Environmental personnel arrived on scene to contain and clean the release. Upon arrival, a mini-excavator and skid steer were utilized to recover the hazardous waste material in the impacted area, that measured approximately 30-feet (ft.) x 80-ft. The recovered material was direct-loaded into three, 25-yard roll-off containers and transported off-site by Ace to their facility pending transportation and delivery to generator (i.e., Maryland DOT Port Administration). In addition, absorbent booms were placed in the ditch-swale area as directed by MDE personnel on-site.

A third party called the police to report our trailer was venting or white cloud coming from rear cabinet doors.  Highway patrol pulled over our unit to inspect. They moved to exit off I-40 just east of OKC because it was safer to troubleshoot.  Local Pryor personnel were dispatched to assist the driver. They found the bottom fill valve was leaking product. They warmed the valve using buckets of water and were able to close the valve enough to return to the Pryor terminal. Pryor Management confirmed with police that this was ok.
column169: The valve was replaced.  Training was held with all drivers to reinforce that all valves should be hand tightened (per design) rather than using a valve wrench on them.  We will follow-up to ensure training and procedures specifically state valves designed for hand tightening should never be tightened with valve wrenches.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: During routine facility staging operations, a transport trailer was identified to have had a release. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified through internal health and safety departments, trained facility personnel entered the trailer to identify the compromised container. Once identified, personnel were successful in safely placing the container into a UN specification salvage drum and remediation of the transport trailer.The release was contained to the transport trailer only; no land, soil, water ways or storm drains were impacted by the release. The container was sent to its final destination disposal facility without further incident.
column169: At the time of acceptance of the container, there was no evidence of release or container integrity issues. The generator was notified of the release.

column168: Driver 1103045 advised that he finished unloading cmpt 1 and disconnected the hose and set it on his spill bucket. The hose shifted and knocked the bucket over which had about 1-2" of product in it. Estimating about 1 qaurt spilled out. The consignee rinsed it down.
column169: Driver was brought in for training.  We revisited the correct process is to disconnect the hose and cap it right away so it can be laid on the ground. This would have prevented the hose from shifting and the bucket tipping over.

column168: During a delivery of both sodium hypochlorite and hydrochloric acid to a pool at the Central City Convention Center the driver successfully delivered to the hypochlorite tank.  He then flushed his lines and began the delivery to the hydrochloric acid tank.  During the delivery to the hydrochloric acid tank the driver mistakenly placed the pump into the wrong IBC and pumped approximately 30 gallons of sodium hypochlorite solution into the  hydrochloric acid tank.  This mixture released approximately 30lbs of chlorine gas into the atmosphere.  There was a water aerobics class and other users in the pool adjacent to the chemical storage room where the accidental mixing took place.  Approximately 24 persons and our employee in the pool area were transported to the hospital.  All but 4 were seen and discharged after monitoring for chlorine exposure.
column169: Hawkins is reviewing their procedures utilized in this case.  This incident will be used to train employees about the consequences of accidental mixing.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, STABILIZED OR HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column168: THE TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER HYDROGEN PEROXIDE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK WHEN THE DELIVERY HOSE RUPTURED. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE WAS RELEASED. SOME OF THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE WAS ABLE TO SPRAY ONTO THE DELIVERY DRIVER WHO ENDED UP SEEKING MEDICAL ATTENTION. THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM A LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITY. THE CUSTOMER WAS ABLE TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL WITHOUT INCIDENT. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC WILL REPLACE THE DAMAGED HOSE IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE KAG WEST, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE HOSE AND HOSE ADAPTER TO THE STORAGE TANK BECAME COMPROMISED AND APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE  AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KAG WEST, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: THE NORTH CANTON TRANSFER, LLC DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION AND WAS PREPARING TO DELIVER MOLTEN SULFUR INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THE UNLOADING LINE ON THE TRAILER WAS BLOCKED WITH HARDENED SULFUR. HEAT WAS APPLIED TO THE TRAILER WHICH ULTIMATELY CAUSED PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER TO BUILD AND PUSH OUT APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF SULFUR THROUGH AN OPEN DOME LID. EAP INDUSTRIAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND ASSISTED WITH THE CLEAN-UP. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: NORTH CANTON TRANSFER, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING AND UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: The driver was loading a full load of 87 gasoline at the Buckeye Terminal Bay 2.   The loading arm hooked to compartment #2 of the trailer had a control valve malfunction, this lead to the compartment to being over loaded.  Approximately 75 gallons of gasoline was spilled out the trailer dome lid as a result of the malfunction.  The rack operator hit the emergency stop button, the top of the trailer was cleaned off and the product spilled on the ground was cleaned up using booms and spill pads.
column169: Continued communication on loading SOP and spill response.

column168: THE PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANKS. AFTER COMPLETING DELIVERY INTO ONE TANK, THE DRIVER FAILED TO CAP OFF THE TANK. WHEN HE WAS DELIVERING INTO A SECOND TANK THAT IS MANIFOLDED TO THE FIRST TANK, APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS ABLE TO BE RELEASED FROM THE FIRST TANK. MASTERS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: During routine facility inspections, facility personnel identified a compromised container resulting in a small release of its contents. In appropriate personal protective equipment, personnel were successful in overpacking the compromised container and remediation of the trailer floor. This release was contained to the transport trailer floor with no impact to land, soil, water ways or storm drains. The container was sent to its final destination without further incident.

column169: RECOMMENDED CORRECTIVE ACTIONS CONTINUE TO BE DISCUSSED AND EVALUATED INTERNALLY, HOWEVER, THEY OR MAY NOT INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING:  ADDITIONAL TECHNOLOGY  TRAINING  DRIVER PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: At the RSI facility it is their company policy that they load our tanker.  Our drivers are not allowed to assist with the loading.  After the loading was completed the operator failed to close the belly valves.  While exiting the facility our driver hit a fence post, tearing and dislodging the belly pipes from the tanker.  Due to the belly valves not being closed the spill occurred.  The driver re-positioned the tanker to gain access to close the belly valves, mitigating the amount spilled.  Approximately 1804 gallons spilled on to an asphalt lot and drained to a dirt gravel lot.  95% of the product evaporated.  The fire department was called they evacuated the facility.  After approximately 2 hours the vast majority of the spill had evaporated and they deemed the area safe to return.  HEPACO (an environmental response company) responded and proceeded to clean up the remaining residue utilizing a vac truck.  Over the next three days HEPACO removed and properly disposed of all the contaminated soil and replaced with new gravel and soil.  Petroleum Carriers pumped off the remaining product into another tanker and proceeded to deliver to the customer.
column169: We feel the biggest lesson learned from this incident was to insure all belly valves are closed after loading and during transit.  The second lesson was even though this was seasoned driver we felt all our employees needed re-training on the purpose and location of the emergency shut off.  Petroleum Carriers have re-evaluated our procedures in both areas and re-educated our employees on the significance of both lessons learned.  We also have reached out to RSI to evaluate their procedures to insure the belly valves are closed after loading and to give our driver access to see that consignee.  The tanker has been taken to a repair facility to be repaired and re tested.

column168: MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT WHILE TRANSPORTING A TANKER LOAD OF ETHANOLAMINE IN ROUTE FROM HOUSTON TO ARNOLD MO. WHILE IN HOUSTON, THE DRIVER TOOK A WRONG TURN WHICH PLACED HIM ON A NARROW STREET. WHILE ATTEMPTING TO NAVIGATE A RIGHT, HAD TURN ONTO ANOTHER STREET, THE REAR TRAILER TANDEMS DROPPED OFF OF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT WHICH RESULTED IN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER BEING TURNED OVER ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE. HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO SCENE AND WE ALSO ENGAGED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY-TEXAS HAZMAT AND SENT THEM TO THE SCENE. THE TANKER DID NOT RUPTURE, NOR WAS IT LEAKING PER THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY. INITIALLY IT WAS THOUGH THAT THERE COULD HAVE BEEN A LEAK AND NRC WAS CALLED AS A PRECAUTION. LATER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRUCK HAD RELEASED 5-8 GALLONS OF MOTOR FLUIDS AND 1-2 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. TEXAS HAZMAT CREW AND THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT DEVELOPED A PLAN TO TRANSFER THE LOAD TO ANOTHER TANKER. THE LOAD WAS SUCCESSFULLY TRANSFERRED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE FINAL DESTINATION. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF MOTOR FLUIDS AND DIESEL FUEL WERE CLEANED UP BY THE RESPONSE CREW AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

column168: SENERGY TRUCK WAS STOPPED BEHIND ONE VEHICLE AT A TRAFFIC SIGNAL AT THE INTERSECTION OF S. COUNTRY CLUB AND SOUTHERN AVE, MESA, AZ. A PICKUP WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY BEHIND THE SENERGY TRUCK. A THIRD VEHICLE OPERATED BY A INDIVIDUAL NAMED "ANTWANN" IN THE POLICE REPORT STRUCK THE PICKUP DRIVING IT FORWARD INTO THE BACK OF THE SENERGY TANKER TRAILER. THE SENERGY DRIVER HAD MAINTAINED A SAFE DISTANCE FROM THE VEHICLE IN FRONT OF IT AND WHILE PUSHED FORWARD A FEW FEET DID NOT STRIKE THE VEHICLE STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM. THE POLICE REPORT INCORRECTLY INDICATES THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH GASOLINE WHEN IN FACT IT WAS LOADED WITH DIESEL. SENERGY DRIVER WAS NOT CITED AND WAS RELEASED TO LEAVE THE SCENE AFTER THE INVESTIGATION. WE HAVE NO KNOWLEDGE OF ANY CITATIONS TO THE OTHER PARTIES. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FROM THE SENERGY TANKER. THE TRAILER SUFFERED NO STRUCTURAL DAMAGE OF ANY TYPE AND DID NOT REQUIRE ANY REPAIRS. ATTACHED ARE THE POLICE REPORTS VERIFYING THIS INFORMATION.  DAMAGE TO SENERGY TRUCK WAS 0. THERE WAS DAMAGE TO THE OTHER TWO VEHICLES BUT THE AMOUNT IS UNKNOWN. NO INJURIES FOR SENERGY PERSONNEL. EMERGENCY MEDICAL WAS ON SCENE BUT NO INJURY REPORTS WERE SHARED WITH SENERGY.  ATTACHMENTS INCLUDE: POLICE REPORT, BOL, US DOT LETTER DATED 6 JUNE, 2019
column169: NO RECOMMENDATIONS FOR ACTIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE AS THE SENERGY DRIVER WAS OPERATING IN TOTAL COMPLIANCE WITH DOT, HAZMAT, AND SENERGY OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES.
